# LETTER TO DOUGLAS RUSHKOFF
## Author, "Team Human"
## Media Theorist, Queens College

---

**Douglas Rushkoff**
Professor of Media Theory, Queens College
Author, *Team Human*, *Throwing Rocks at the Google Bus*, *Present Shock*

---

Dear Professor Rushkoff,

You've spent your career warning us that technology optimized for extraction will extract. That digital platforms designed to scale will scale exploitation. That the operating system matters more than the apps running on it.

I've spent fifteen years trying to build a different operating system.

My name is Jonathan Jones. I'm 52, an ARNG veteran, helicopter pilot, father of eight. I've invested $5,000 annually from a $30,000 income into this — 47 years thinking about cooperative economics, 15 years actively building.

**The "Team Human" Problem**

In *Team Human*, you wrote that we need to reclaim the social space from platforms designed to extract attention and data. In *Throwing Rocks at the Google Bus*, you argued that the digital economy's core problem isn't technology — it's the operating system running beneath it.

I agree. And I think I've built a different operating system.

**Liana Banyan's Architecture**

The platform operates on one principle: **Cost + 20%**.

Creators keep **83.3%** of every transaction. The margin is locked in the operating agreement — not a policy that can change, but architecture that cannot. If someone buys Liana Banyan, the margin stays locked. If leadership changes, the margin stays locked. If we go public (we won't), the margin stays locked.

We cannot enshittify because the legal structure prevents it.

Three commercial divisions fund fourteen charitable initiatives:

**Food & Home:** Let's Make Dinner, Let's Get Groceries, Let's Go Shopping, Home Logistics
**Health & Safety:** LifeLine Medications, MSA, Defense Klaus, Rally Group
**Finance & Work:** VSL (microfinance), Let's Make Bread (manufacturing), Harper Guild (ethics)
**Creative & Learning:** JukeBox (music), Didasko (education), International

**The 15-Year Trail**

| Milestone | Date |
|-----------|------|
| Localcy Currency Exchange Credit (LCEC) | 2010-2011 |
| SolidWorks prototypes (active duty Army) | 2003 |
| Patent portfolio | 150+ innovations, 470+ claims |
| First provisional filed | #63/925,672 (Nov 26, 2025) |

This isn't a startup that pivoted to "social good." It's fifteen years of work on the same economic theory, refined through 18 handwritten journals and 1,200+ technical diagrams.

**The Challenge**

You've written about corporate personhood, about how legal structures encode values that then seem inevitable. I've tried to use that same mechanism in reverse — encoding cooperative values into a legal structure so they become inevitable too.

The question: Does it work? Or have I just built another extraction machine with better marketing?

**Why I'm Writing**

I'm not asking for endorsement. I'm asking for the same critical eye you bring to every digital platform.

You understand how technology encodes values. You've mapped how extraction becomes structural. If there's a flaw in what I've built — some way the operating system still favors extraction over cooperation — I need to know.

The documentation is at **Cephas.LianaBanyan.org**. The operating agreement is published.

Would you be willing to examine it? I'd rather hear that it's broken from you than learn it's broken after thousands of people depend on it.

Respectfully,

**Jonathan Jones**
Founder, Liana Banyan Corporation
406-578-1232

---

There is a walkthrough at [LianaBanyan.com/RedCarpet](https://lianabanyan.com/RedCarpet). No scheduling, no pitch deck, no salesman.

Help each other help ourselves.

As You Wish.
Founder@LianaBanyan.com

---

*"Help each other help ourselves."*

**Documentation:** Cephas.LianaBanyan.org
**Patent:** #63/925,672

---

P.S. — I listen to Team Human. The episode with Astra Taylor on technology and democracy was particularly relevant to what I'm trying to build.
