# LETTER: PARIS MARX
## Host, Tech Won't Save Us
## Platform Critic & Author

**Date:** January 23, 2026

---

Dear Paris,

You've spent years documenting how tech platforms promise liberation and deliver extraction.

I've spent nine years building the one that might actually deliver liberation.

I listen to *Tech Won't Save Us* because you ask the questions other tech journalists won't: Who benefits? Who pays? What happens to workers? Your skepticism isn't cynicism — it's pattern recognition. You've seen this movie before. The promises. The pivot. The extraction.

I'm writing because I built something different, and I want you to be skeptical of it.

---

## WHO I AM

I'm a 53-year-old ARNG veteran — Infantry and Aviation, helicopter pilot with FAA Commercial Rotary Wing IFR rating. Father of eight. 21 years in IT development. Not a tech founder with VC backing and exit strategy. Not a former Google engineer "democratizing" something.

I've been thinking about cooperative economics for four decades. Building this for nine. I have 18 handwritten journals documenting every iteration, 1,200+ technical diagrams, and 150+ innovations with 928 patent claims filed.

I've mortgaged my house. No venture capital. No board of investors demanding growth at any cost.

I'm an amateur engineer from Texas who got angry at the right things and decided to build rather than complain.

---

## WHAT I'VE BUILT

Liana Banyan is a cooperative platform built on one principle: **Cost + 20%**.

That's it. The platform margin is fixed in the operating agreement. Creators keep 83.3% of every transaction. The remaining 16.7% funds operations and fourteen charitable initiatives — food security, healthcare access, education, financial inclusion, crisis response. Not through donations. Through commerce. The structure generates the funding automatically, forever.

I know what you're thinking: *Everyone says they're different.*

So let me tell you what makes this actually different:

---

## WHY THIS ISN'T THE USUAL BULLSHIT

**On extraction:**
- DoorDash takes 30%+. We take 16.7%.
- But more importantly: their margin can increase. Ours can't. It's in the operating agreement.
- We can't enshittify because we're contractually prohibited from doing so.

**On labor:**
- Workers choose their compensation model (cash, revenue share, hybrid)
- Workers elect their own representative to the corporate Board
- Every initiative includes a Harper — a care coordinator paid by the platform, not the business

**On ownership:**
- Participation creates ownership stakes (Platform Joules)
- Not equity grants from a generous founder — structural ownership by design
- The more you contribute, the more you own

**On AI:**
- Our AI system (Star Chamber) is designed for verification, not surveillance
- It prevents hallucination and ensures quality
- Workers aren't rated by opaque algorithms — they're evaluated by peers

**On the exit:**
- There is no exit strategy
- No acquisition plans
- No IPO
- The platform is designed to outlive its founder, not enrich him

---

## YOUR QUESTIONS, ANTICIPATED

*"Who funds this?"*
Me. My mortgage. Some small donations. No venture capital. No growth-at-any-cost investors.

*"What's your business model?"*
Cost + 20% on transactions. Membership fees ($5/year). That's it.

*"What happens when you need to scale?"*
We've built manufacturing nodes — distributed production facilities where operators keep 60% of their time for scheduled work and 40% for their own projects. Scaling doesn't require extraction; it requires more nodes.

*"What about regulation?"*
Members are cooperative members, not misclassified contractors. Platform Credits are reward points, not securities. The structure is designed to work within regulation, not around it.

*"Why should I believe you?"*
You shouldn't. Yet. That's why I'm inviting you to examine it.

---

## WHAT I'M ASKING

I want you to investigate this.

Not puff piece. Investigation. Talk to me on record. Review the documents. Find the contradictions. Ask the hard questions.

If Liana Banyan is the usual tech platform bullshit dressed up in cooperative language, expose it. Your audience deserves to know.

If it's actually different — if we've built the thing that proves tech *can* save us when structured correctly — your audience deserves to know that too.

Either way, the truth serves everyone.

---

## THE INTERVIEW

I'm available for *Tech Won't Save Us* whenever you want.

I won't have PR handlers. I won't have talking points approved by lawyers. I'll answer your questions directly, including the uncomfortable ones.

The worst thing that can happen is you find structural problems I haven't seen. The best thing is you help people understand that alternatives exist.

---

## THE CONNECTION

You've documented how platform capitalism extracts value from workers and communities while promising empowerment.

I built a platform that actually empowers — by locking extraction out of the legal structure.

Maybe I'm wrong. Maybe there's hidden extraction I'm not seeing. If so, I need someone like you to find it.

Tech won't save us. But maybe the right tech, structured correctly, governed cooperatively, can help us save ourselves.

Help each other help ourselves.

---

With respect for your skepticism,

**Jonathan Jones**
Founder, Liana Banyan Corporation
Founder@LianaBanyan.com
406-578-1232

---

There is a walkthrough at [LianaBanyan.com/RedCarpet](https://lianabanyan.com/RedCarpet). No scheduling, no pitch deck, no salesman.

Help each other help ourselves.

As You Wish.

---

**Enclosures:**
- A Considered Approach to Sustained Universal Economic Prosperity (Academic Paper)
- The Economics of Cost + 20%
- Operating Agreement excerpts showing locked margin
$md_paris_marx$
